                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Of course you can't solo the Emp for the rift, but you can solo every other part of it...even the Orb of Lucinite if you're good / lucky.  
<br />

<br />
So let's gets started.  This is old world charming; spell line up 98% of the time will be the following:
<br />

<br />
1. Pacification
<br />
2. Fetter or G. Fetter or Root (You're preference, sometimes you need long root parks)
<br />
3. Tash
<br />
4. GoK (Occasionally Apathy is needed)
<br />
5. Forlorn Deeds
<br />
6. Beckon
<br />
7. Word of Morrel
<br />
8. Arcane Rune
<br />

<br />
I suggest always getting a PoT9 and SOE / SoW before each shard, they come in very handy.  You're also going to need a few sow potions, some pet weapons are nice, and how could we forget our Blue Ceramic Band.  
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-size: 18px; line-height: normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">The Shards </span></span></span>
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Dat </span></span>- <span style="font-weight: bold">Fungus Grove </span>(Difficulty - Medium) from Shik`Nar Warriors and Royals, confirmed from: Shik`nar Warrior and Shik`nar Royal Guard
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.eqatlas.com/luclin/fungusgrovemap.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">EQ Atlas Map</a> - Tells you how to get to the caves
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://home.cinci.rr.com/cennyan/images/vtshard/fungusgrove.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Nothing sees invis in these caves that I've ever seen, so buff up, invis up and head back to the red dot.  The two mobs to the west of you will be Soldiers, the northern gold dot is the Priest and the Southern is another Soldier.  There is a soldier where the red dot is as well.  Mez the Soldier at the camp spot,  Tash, Beckon, SoS and Guard.  Pacify the Priest and 3 of the warriors in the 4-spawn room, then pull.  Repeat till that room is cleared then move in.  You have two options...if you don't feel comfortable pulling another room in the time span you have, then simply camp this room killing the spawns off as they pop.  If you do feel you have enough time however, simply pacify the soldier in the hallway to the south, pacify one of the Royal Guards and pull the other.  When it's dead, pull the last one.   That's it.  It's a pretty easy camp overall but can get harry when charm breaks.  Always keep your opponent mob rooted, and keep a distance between you and your pet and you should be all right. 
<br />

<br />
There is a 2-spawn of Warriors in the very first cave.   It's not very easy to keep cleared if you're soloing, but if you're grouped it can be done.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Kel</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">The Grey </span>(Difficulty - Easy) confirmed from: A Sun Revenant (near the lake)
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.eqatlas.com/luclin/thegreymap.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Link to EQAtlas Map</a>
<br />

<br />
This one's very easy.  Make you're way up to the pond in the NW corner.  You want to pull to, and camp, the area just NE of the pond on the hill.  To the NW of the pond is a rock formation in which 1-3 golem mobs will spawn.  They're not too tough, but annoying none the less and do not serve our purpose, so simply avoid the rock formation unless you're insanely bored.  
<br />

<br />
To break and clear the camp, simply Pacify one of the mobs near the NE corner, then pull the one next to it with Tash.  Mez it, Charm it, Buff it and Guard, then work you're way around the pond.  I suggest going clockwise as it's easier to avoid the rock formation.  The mobs closest to the rock formation can be pulled from the opposite side of the lake.  When mobs here go into their death march, they will start walking south.  When they get past the lake area, it's very possible for them to agro adds.  Keep death walking mobs rooted to prevent getting adds.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Kelera</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">Sanctus Seru or Katta </span>(Difficulty (Seru)- Easy (Katta not sure), confirmed from: A Legionnaire of the Hand, Named Legionnaires in the upper level of Sanctus Seru, An Intervallum Guard, and Various Katta centurions (too many to list)
<br />

<br />
Another Easy one.  Zone into Seru and run through the tunnel to the city opening.  Turn right and just around the corner you'll see a portal.  Click on it and you'll be in the upper hallways.  Every mob in the hall has the chance of dropping a shard.  Before charming a pet, take a look at what you're charming.  Some mobs here dual-wield and are already holding two weapons...some dual wield and are holding a shield.  For pets, I tried to ensure I chose only mobs that were already dual-wielding.  The only tough part about this shard is that you can sometimes get adds, and they do sometimes add up.  I had 4 adds at one point, but was fine.  Once you clear a couple of mobs, you can always keep max distance between you and your pet so that when charm breaks, you have plenty of time to recharm.  As always, keep the mob you're killing rooted.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Lor</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">Dawnshroud Peaks</span> (Difficulty - Easy)from Rockhoppers and Sambata in the cave, confirmed from: Sambata Tribal Worker and A Rockhopper Ravager
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.eqatlas.com/luclin/dawnshroudpeaksmap.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Link to EQAtlas Map</a>
<br />

<br />
Very easy.  So much in fact I wont give too much detail.  Go to the caves marked 3 on EQ Atlas map.  Charm something and start killing stuff.  You can easily handle any adds.  Most of the mobs here are green and light blue so you can use Boltrans instead of Beckon.  I actually camped this solo with my twink monk (L53) since they were still blue to him, then camped and logged in my enc when the shard dropped.  You could probably AE this camp with a wiz / mag or cleric.  This and the Scarlet Desert Shard are as easy as it gets.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Raf</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">The Deep </span>(Difficutly - Easy) from Thought Horrors across the bridge, confirmed from: A Thought Horror Spiriter and A Thought Horror
<br />

<br />
[img=http://www.eqmaps.com/m3/thedeep2.jpg]Link to EQMaps Map[/img]
<br />

<br />
The hard part to this I suppose is not getting lost in the caves <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  Most mobs prior to the bridge do not see invis, however, some do.  Buff up at IZ, invis up and make you're way back.  I suggest conning everything as you move just to make sure.  If you find a see invis mob, find a safe spot to pacify from, then keep moving.  The mobs you want will be just east of the "fake bridge" on the above map.  Most (if not all) of the Thought Horrors are uncharmable, however the shrooms and other mobs nearby are.  NOTE: You DO NOT have to cross the bridge.  Shards drop on any Spiriter or Thought Horror in the zone.  When you enter the main chasm chamber, you'll note that there are about 6 or 7 thought horrors at this spot.  This is a prime area to solo camp your shard from; It's easy to train zone if you have to, and if you don't make it, it's easy to get your corpse.  There is a roamer that goes through the area, and that roamer makes an excellent pet <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Set</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">The Scarlet Desert </span>(Difficulty - Easy) from Sun Revenants and Reavers on the Plateau, confirmed from: A Sun Revenant and A Sun Reaver
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.eqatlas.com/luclin/scarletdesertmap.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Link to EQ Atlas Map</a>
<br />

<br />
Another extremely easy one.  Head to the plateau in the NE corner of the map.  Charm something and start killing Revenants and Reavers.  I brought my wizard with me and we AE'd everything for this one just to save time.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Tak</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">Maiden's Eye </span>(Difficulty - Medium) from named Goranga, confirmed from: A Goranga Battlemaster, A Goranga Forager, A Goranga Prophet, A Goranga Savant, A Goranga Seer
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://home.cinci.rr.com/cennyan/images/vtshard/meshardmap.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
If I had to pick one zone I hated more than any other, ME would be it.  Be ready for adds, and be ready for a potentially long camp.  The spawn times on most of the PH's seems to be right around 25-30 minutes.  I got insanely bored in the fifth hour of this camp, logged on my wizard, and would pull the three camps closest to ME all at the same time with the wizard.  I'd usually end up with 7 Goranga, and one or two adds.  I'd mezz 2-4, Make one a pet, haste it, then kill the 2-4 mezzed while my wizard would quad kite four.  The difficulty with this camp causing it to have a medium rating is attributed to the randomness of spawns.  I've watched the pathing in this zone, and it doesn't seem that any single mob here has a set roaming path, and  that the 
<br />

<br />
Note that the Chief and Spiritseer at the 5 spawn tree do not drop shards to my knowledge (I've heard they can, but I've never had anyone confirm it).  The other five spawn points are all around rocks and each named almost always drops the shard.  The problem is that they named are rare as hell.  The two rocks furthest to the north (Seer, Forager and Savant PHs) each have three goranga.  The Battlemaster spawn has 2, and the Prophet spawn has 3 but is broken up far enough that one of the non-PH mobs will not agro.  I'll give my advice for each camp.
<br />

<br />
Seer Stone - Not too rough.  The trick here is to avoid adds while pacifying.  I would pacify the two non-PH, then charm the PH and send him against the five mobs at the tree, run to the zoneline, then when the PH pet would die, zone out.  You can choose to charm kite the PH with one of the non-PH at the rocks, but the fastest method is what I did.  If the Seer spawns, Pacify him and one non-PH, charm the other and pull the Seer over by the zone along the hill.  Keep in mind he can and will gate, so be ready for it. 
<br />

<br />
Forager / Savant stone - This is the toughest of the four stones.  It's a 3 Goranga spawn and it's in an extremely high traffic area.  To top that off, there are tons of mobs that are prox activated..ie.."The ground erupts at your feet" and a mob will spawn.  If you are not extremely comfortable handling multiple mobs while performing pacify's, mezes and pulls, then skip this stone.  
<br />

<br />
What I would do is wait for a window of low traffic, then pacify the non-PH.  I would pull both PH's back to the area marked camp to the west of the AR zoneline.  Ideally, you want to get just the two, then charm kite them.  To do this, pull with Tash, Run up the hill a bit, invis, then run back to the camp.  The roaming mobs will not agro with the two PH's if you are invis usually.  Some however do see invis so be careful.  Don't haste or slow, just let them have at each other and they will both drop at about the same rate.  However, ME is far from an ideal zone and you will more than likey get adds while pulling.  If you do, it's your choice as to what to charm.  I typically grabbed the first mob that made its way into camp.  Kill off the PH's at least.  If you have excessive adds, then zone to AR to save time.  If it's just one, then it's probably quicker to just kill it.  When a named spawn, try to follow the same scenario.  Charm the non-PH, slow the named (or haste pet or both) and they'll both drop easily.
<br />

<br />
Battlemaster Stone - Cut and dry and very easy.  Wait till their are no roamers nearby, pull both back to the camp spot, charm one and kill the other.  Don't haste or slow and both will drop life at approximately the same rate.  When the BM spawns, same thing except use slow to balance the mobs DPS.  You're choice to haste your pet.  I would sometimes keep the pet from this and use pacify to single pull the PH at the prophet stone and save some time.  Again, totally up to you.
<br />

<br />
Prophet Stone - Not overly difficult.  There's three mobs at the stone, one is off to the west and wont agro when you pull the two to the east of the stone.  This is a Medium Traffic area for roamers, so make sure you're on your toes.  Pull the PH and the non PH Up the hill to the south of their spawn point.  Once they clear the stone, start heading West towards your camp.  Keep an eye out for roamers.  When the PH spawns follow the same scenerio.  The prophet is obviously a caster and will stop to cast spells on you, make sure you don't get too far ahead and lose agro.  The Prophet can and WILL gate, so be ready for it.
<br />

<br />
Overall, it's not too tough.  The pain comes from all the roamers, see invis mobs and random spawning adds.  The camp area is completely safe though.  I have never seen a roamer or random spawn in that area and I was there for about 10 hours camping my shard <img src="images/smiles/icon_sad.gif" alt="icon_sad.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Ved</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">Acrylia Cavern </span>(Difficulty - Medium) from Grimlings in Inner Acrylia, confirmed from: A Grimling Prison Guard, A Grimling Deathguard and A Sanctum Bloodguard
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.eqmaps.com/m3/acrylia1.jpg" target="_blank" class="postlink">Link to EQMaps Map</a>
<br />

<br />
You'll need to make you're way to the point on the map where it says "Entrance to Inner Acrylia" and talks about a key.  You no longer need a key however.  On the way to that room though you will need to pacify the skeletons.  I suggest standing just past the gate, pacify the Shiknar to the left and ahead, move up some and then pacify the two skelies to the east of the stairs, the one on the Northeast corner of the stairs, and the Northeast corner mob on top of the stairs.  There is a roamer that comes by the gate, if he's nearby he'll need a hit of pacification as well.  Once the Skelies are pacified, invis and head back.  Go into the room mentioned above, and click on the statue.  This will deposit you in a small room in Inner Acrylia.  This is the best spot to pull and kill in.  The hallways all have multiple roamers and the first time I tried soloing in the hall I got 5 adds, charm broke and I got creamed.  You're best bet is to stay in the room you pop up in.
<br />

<br />
The bad part about these mobs is that they have a very hard push when they hit you and will almost always interrupt your spells.  I kept up Word of Morrell and Color Spray for this purpose.  When charm would break, I'd spray, Morrel then either mez or recharm.  I suggest taking a bloodguard or deathguard as a pet.  Yes, they can drop a shard, but all the other mobs back here are casters and do not make very good pets.  They'll end up casting forever while the mob is pounding on you.  Pull whatever you feel comfortable pulling.  Pacify as needed.  Every mob near you, and in the big room, can spawn a shard mob, so there's no need to selectively kill.  Of course, kill all the bloodguards and deathguards you see before clearing everything else...maybe you'll get lucky and get the shard right off the bat.  
<br />

<br />
The fact that the mobs push and interrupt is the only thing that makes this camp difficult.   
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Vin</span></span> - <span style="font-weight: bold">Ssraeshza Temple </span>(Difficulty - Hard) from Skeletons in the Mines, confirmed from: A Soriz Corpse and A Soriz Drudge
<br />

<br />
This one is pretty tough.  Unless you're very competent at soloing, I recommend you do this camp with a group.  If you are competent then keep reading.  
<br />

<br />
I wont enclose a map, if you want to solo this shard, you should know the caverns pretty well and how to get there.  Make you're way down avoiding all the normal hazards in Ssra.  Sometimes the Skelies can see invis, sometimes they don't.  Use caution.  You either need to invis back to the middle caves where the drudges and soriz's spawn or you need to clear back there.  The really hard part about this is the chain agro.  I died 2 times trying to solo this shard because of it.  Even with pacify, you'll sometime get crazy agro.  Might be a good place to keep gate up.  
<br />

<br />
You'll want to use Soriz Slaves as your pet.  They're melee based and with a couple of good weapons can mow stuff down.  I can't remember which, but either the Soriz Corpse or the Drudge can fear, so keep GoD up on you and your pet at all times.  For the same reason, neither the Soriz Corpses or Drudges make good pets.  If your pet gets feared, I highly recommend gating if fear doesn't break right away otherwise you're going to find out exactly how many mobs are in the mines.  
<br />

<br />
I would suggest clearing back to the 7 spawns near the Deep Zoneline.  No roamers make their way back there, and it's not to difficult to keep the room cleared.  If you feel you have a good grasp on the spawn, then maybe take out a few more from the hallway as well.  
<br />

<br />
Good luck if you try to solo this one.  It's fun as can be, but it's very dangerous.  Tactics pit is easier in my opinion.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Dax</span></span> - Akheva Ruins (Difficulty - Medium) confirmed from: A Shadow Reaver, A Shade Golem, A Rubble Rouser and Shaded Stones.
<br />

<br />
I saved this for last because you need two things from AR.  You need a shard and the scepter frame to combine the shards in.  I'll describe getting your shard first. 
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://home.cinci.rr.com/cennyan/images/vtshard/akheva.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Ok, First I'll describe what you see on the map.  For the purposes of camping shards, the only room you really need to be in will be the first Main Chamber past the fallen pillar room.  If you trigger a trap or get excessive adds getting back to this point, take them to zone.  It's much easier than trying to fight it all.  
<br />

<br />
Start out with a Centi Dator pet.  Give him a couple weapons and some haste.  My main goal was Shadow Reavers.  I would pull some of the golems, but not many.  I highly recommend you don't pull Rubble Rousers as they have about 100k HP and you'll be fighting them for a good while.  I'd pull Shade Golems and Shaded Stones as I could.   NOTE:  Some Dators are immune to everything (Root, Snare, Charm and Mez), if you try to charm one and unable to control it, zone it.  
<br />

<br />
Wherever you see a red dot on the map is a potential floor trap.  These traps will spawn either 1-3 Shaded Reavers or 2-7 Mind Worms.  My main Strategy was simply to keep the main chamber cleared and trigger as many traps as I could.  Mind worms can be a total pain if they all agro on you, so keep some stuns and Word of Morrel up.  Get them mezzed fast or they will totally drain you of mana in a matter of moments.  Shadow Reavers make great pets btw, even better than the Dators.  Once you get a few to spawn, you may want to consider using one as a pet instead of the Dator.  They have more HP and better DPS than the Dators.  There are a few roamers that go through here, but overall the camp itself is not difficult at all.  If you get more than you can chew, then take it to zone and rebreak no sweat.  
<br />

<br />
It's a pretty fun camp and decent loots.  Mind Worms drop hides which sell for quite a bit to tailors in the bazaar, or if you're like me, save them for yourself <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  Centi's and worms both drop meat which makes pretty decent food, and Shadow Reavers occasionally drop Shaded Weapons...great weapons for pets and probably sell decently in the bazaar as well.  
<br />

<br />
OK...so you got all your shards and now you want to empty up the spots they take up in your bank.  Get yourself a Wisp Stone from a mage (They are no rent) and an essence emerald.  You need to make your way back to the Sacrificial Pit.  Same rules apply moving their as moving to the main shard camp.  If you trigger a trap and get add's, it's almost better to zone it then to fight it, but entirely up to you.  
<br />

<br />
Invis all the way back to the mob which is indicated as the Pacify Mob.  You want to pacify him by moving just south of him and west of the static mob in the center of the room.  Once he's pacified, move up by him on the ledge and using your Blue Ceramic Band, kill off each of the remains one at a time.  Give each remains a few seconds before killing the next one.  <span style="font-weight: bold">NOTE:  You can NOT see the shimmering Presence from where you're killing off the remains.  Once all the remains are dead, click the area where they are to see if you can target the presence.</span>  When the Shimmering Presence finally spawns, you'll need to pacify the four chanting shades in the middle of the room.  I'm not sure if you need to pacify the three  Atulinae'Vius's at the top of the platform, but I did anyway to make sure.  
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">Orb of Lucinite</span></span>
<br />

<br />
Well, in all honesty this isn't going to be easy to solo and I'd say 99% of the chanters who do this quest wont be able to solo for this piece.  Orb's drop off of just about all Luclin named mobs, so they are somewhat common.  There are, however, a few boss mobs that can be done by 1 group and even less.  VaDynn (AR), Rhag 1 (Ssra), Servitor of Luclin (Griegs) can all be killed by a single group.  I've killed Rhag 1 and SoL with as few as three people and a pet, and I'm convinced that SoL can be soloed.  I have yet to try it, but I'm going to very soon.  You can invis all the way back to his room.  He's L65, slowable and summons.  There's four blue guards in his room for pet fodder, and once he's slowed he's pretty weak, so even if you get summoned you should be OK.  The only bad point would be charm breaking with a hasted pet.  There's not a lot of room to play around with.  Again though, I definitely think he is soloable.  I would imagine that it's possible to solo the other three mobs as well, but it would be very difficult and require a great skill.  Good luck to you if you try the solo route and post here to let me know how you did, I'll do the same.  
<br />

<br />
Congrats you on your VT key <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />
